9/15/15, 20:29 - Krishna COE 2: अंग्रेजी के प्रोफेसर से 






एक स्टूडेंट ने पूछा






 कि  सर नटुरे का अर्थ क्या होगा?





प्रोफेसर साहब हैरान!
 




टालने के लिए कह दिया 




कि कल बता दूँगा।
 




उन्होंने
पूरी डिक्शनरी छान मारी,





 किन्तु उन्हें नटुरे शब्द
 नहीं मिला।





अगले दिन 




स्टूडेंट ने फिर से पूछा 





कि सर नटुरे का मतलब क्या होता है?





उस दिन भी उन्होंने बात टाल
 दी।





अब तो वह रोज़ पूछने लगा।





प्रोफेसर साहब उससे
 इतना घबराने लगे
 कि  




 उस लड़के को
 देखते ही रास्ता बदल
 देते,





किन्तु वह रोज़ आकर
 उनको टेँशन देकर चला जाता।




अंत में 




झुँझला कर
 उन्होने उस लड़के से कहा कि
  





मुझे नटुरे
 की स्पेलिंग बताओ।






लड़के ने कहा 
.
.
.
.NATURE
अब तो प्रोफसर साहब का ख़ून खौल गया।





उन्होंने उस लड़के
 से कहा कि
  




मुझे बेवकूफ बनाते हो,
नेचर को नटुरे
 कह कह
 कर तुमने मेरा
 जीना मुश्किल कर दिया था।





मैं तुम्हे कॉलेज 
  से निकलवा दूँगा।





लड़के ने झट से
 प्रोफेसर साहब
 के 




पैर पकड़ लिये
 और रोते रोते कहा कि
  




सर ऐसा अनर्थ
मत कीजिएगा

The Pope comes by. He stops to watch the throngs of people giving money to the beggar who holds the Cross while none give to the beggar holding the Star of David. Finally, the Pope approaches the beggar with the Star of David and says, 
"My poor fellow, don't you understand? This is a Catholic country; this city is the seat of Catholicism. People aren't going to give you money if you sit there with a Star of David in front of you, especially when you're sitting beside a beggar who is holding a Cross. The beggar with the Star of David listened to the Pope, smiled, and turned to the beggar with the Cross and said,  "Jignessbhai, look who's trying to teach the Patel brothers about bijness!"

VENUE: Connecting Block Terrance

The rules of procedure and motions would be declared on the spot. The participants are required to be present on time.

10/4/15, 22:18 - Rajat Singhal: Why do ENGINEERING students always prefer local author books than REFERENCE books???
 The local author says:
'Jack & Jill went up the hill to fetch a pail of water, Jack fell down and broke his crown and Jill came tumbling after'.

 And REFERENCE BOOK says:
'2 humans ascended a certain geological protuberance to collect hydride of oxygen whose quantity is not specified. One member Jack, of rapid irregular disturbing movements encounters fatal logical gravitational error leading to complete disarray. Other member named Jill whose scope lies within disarray, descends down the geographical protuberance at an acceleration, whose magnitude is controlled by the force of gravity.' !!!

10/7/15, 20:20 - Kaushal: Hi.I am writing this message to let you all know about a new initiative that DEBSOC is taking to give back to the college.
If you feel that you are unable to put your points across in a discussion with a group of friends, want to learn how to speak so that people want to listen to you, or want to be more confident when speaking in front of a group, we bring to you an initiative to help YOU.
Here's the idea: We've changed the format of Debsoc's weekly meets to suit YOU, brought in more interactive ways of doing Group Discussions, where you learn:
1. Pressure points of performing in a GD.
2. Points on which the moderators in any GD will assess you.
Secondly, we also focus on extempore speaking in every meet to make you more spontaneous and confident to speak on any and every topic at a moment's notice.

If this is something that interests you, please do attend our weekly meet, Thursday, 4.30, connecting block terrace.

10/8/15, 14:24 - ‪+91 95602 22255‬: "TENSION KAI KO LENE KA"
Ever come across a random page run by a random engineer of some random  engineering college posting the randomest stuff on Facebook? Chances are that you must have. Ever noticed something common? The cliches that surround engineering. The tales about proxies, gaming, LAN (YAY!), chai, sutta, maggi(DOUBLE YAY!) the might seem to be a little silly and overhyped for the non engineering junta. Believe you me. They are true to the core. In every engineering college( and yes, there are lots of them), you will find a pro gamer, you will find a guy who has all the xerox and you’ll be closer to the :maggiwala” than you are to your teachers. As I approach the middle of my third semester in engineering, I have already started to accept the “kadwa sach”. You will never ever learn anything from the teacher, except someone is totally God sent.  Classes will be a matter of attendance strictly. The phase that surrounds engineering is a phase of complete transformation and liberty. There are many choices that are left for you. There are many roads that one might take. Tell me one engineer who does not want to form a startup? Yes, engineers are that typical. So typical that you can classify them into types. Laidback, lazy, dirty, sleepy. Every engineer is known to be one. Whenever one returns back from home, the only thing in mind is “Abbey, yeh sem toh pura parhunga!”. Sincere efforts are taken as well in the first few days. You are regular like anything. Not a single lecture is missed. Not a single assignment is left unsubmitted. But as soon as the sun dawns and a porcupine tree song starts to play loud in the background, you tend to relax a bit. And then you get into typical engineer mode. The “jugadoo” instict inside you starts to reform. “Midsem kharab gaya? Koi nahi, Endsem me 50 utha lenge!” Yes, proclamations as confident and crazy as these are heard from everyone. 

Basically, everyone starts to go through a phase like this and the writer is no stranger to such feelings. Learning to manage disasters in future is only taught by how you manage your sem. In between struggling to manage a sem and trying to maintain composure, I sign off quoting lines from the song that I like to listen to in times such as these-

                     “All my designs, simplified
                     And all of my plans, compromised
                     All of my dreams, sacrificed

                     Arriving somewhere but not here”

10/11/15, 17:50 - ‪+91 88009 17311‬: Check ur presence of mind.............Take d test.

relax, clear your mind and begin, what's the 1st answer that comes to ur mind???...........


1. What do you put in a toaster?














Answer:
"bread." If you said "toast," give up now and do something else.. Try not to hurt yourself. If you said bread, go to Question 2





2. Say "silk" five times. Now spell "silk." What do cows drink?











Answer:
Cows drink water. If you said "milk," don't attempt the next question.
Your brain is over -stressed and may even overheat. Content yourself by reading more appropriate literature such as Auto World. However, if you said "water", proceed to question 3...



3. If a red house is made from red bricks and a blue house is made from blue bricks and a pink house is made from pink bricks and a black house is made from black bricks, what is a
green house made from?














Answer:
Greenhouses are made from glass. If you said "green bricks," why the hell are you still reading these?? If you said "glass," go on to Question 4.




4. It's twenty years ago, and a plane crashes from 20,000 feet over Germany (If you will recall, Germany at the time was politically divided into East and West Germany) Where would you bury the survivors? East Germany, West Germany, "no
man's land"?










Answer: You don't bury survivors!!! If you said ANYTHING else, you must stop. If you said, "You don't bury survivors", proceed to the next question.




5. Without using a calculator - You are driving a bus from Mumbai to Pune. In Mumbai , 17 people get on, in Pune , 16 get off. Name the driver.














Answer: Oh, for crying out loud! Don't you remember your own name? It was YOU!!



😊

A MUST TRY!!!!!!!          ALZHEIMERS'  EYE TEST

(I love this part.. It's absolutely amazing!)

Count every  "  F  " in the following text:

FINISHED  FILES ARE THE RE
SULT OF YEARS OF SCIENTI
FIC STUDY COMBINED  WITH
THE EXPERIENCE OF YEARS...  
(SEE  BELOW)


HOW MANY ? 
  
3....4....

READ IT AGAIN !
Really, go Back and Try to find the  6 F's before you scroll down.


The reasoning behind is  further down.





The brain cannot  process "OF".

Incredible  or what? Go back and look again!!

Anyone who counts  all 6 "F's" on the first go is a genius.

Three  is normal, four is quite rare.

It will drive them crazy!!:

There will be four houses
1)Ravenclaw

10/25/15, 00:30 - ‪+91 97173 79914‬: Engineering ka panchanama 2
........
Problem kya hai?
Problem ye hai ki mai engineering kr raha hu..aur kya problem hai..problem ye hai ki engineering student ki life me koi prob na ho to ye university walon ki sabse badi problem hai..!!  
Basically har student ki life me ek time aata h jab usko apni life me kuch adventure krne ka mann krta h..nd issi chakkar me wo engineering join krtey h.....
University me sabko pass bhi nahi karate..Aur galti se aap semester pass krke aage badh bhi gye to yeh log naye naye tareeke le aate h maarne k!

Sala ek subject k liye mushkil se theory rato to pata chalta hai ki question paper main sare numericals aagaye...abey jab numericals hi dene the paper to humse itna ratwaya kyu? 
passing marks hi dene the tumhe toh..itni ghis te to nahi humari kam se kam....
Aur inn sab k baad bhi coordinator ka mann ni bharta beech beech me saala mazze lene k liye naye naye faltu kaam krwata rehta h..kbhi presentation ,kbhi project nd uske upar kabhi quiz aur viva....
Abey chaar saal me itni baar sessionals lete h ki sala apna roll no. to kya ,apni puri batch ka bhi roll no. tak yaad ho jata hai !
Aur inn sab k baad bhi sabse bada syapa summer training!!
Sala aadhi zindagi to semester pass krne me lag jati h aur baaki sessional dene me!!
Galti se koi company mil jaye to interviewer maarna nhi chodta..!

Engineering kyu choose ki?
Itne back kyu hai ..? 
Jawab do..soch kya rahe ho??
Abey ye soch rha hu ki kis ghadi me mene engineering join ki??
Calculator lga lu dimag me??
Im telling u,a happy engineer is a myth!!
Truly frustrated banda !!  ........

11/12/15, 22:02 - Mannu Baawla: Wait is finally over guys..!! 
Travel Society Of Nsit (TSoC)  present before you all its very first trip to Rajasthan..!! 
Itinerary :
Day 00 (15th Dec): TRIP STARTS
Trip Starts from NSIT at night 9 pm. 

Day 01 (16th  Dec): JAIPUR EXCURSION
Reach  Jaipur  in  the  morning. Freshen up at the  hotel, take breakfast and  leave  for  full  day  sightseeing  of Jaipur.(as per  the  time  permits) Visit  Birla  temple,  drive  through  Johari  Bazaar  (also  known  as  old  jeweler’s market)  to  HawaMahal  i.e Palace  of Winds ,  Amer  Fort. Visit some  of  the  popular  museums inside  the  City  Palace  and  the  ancient observatory,  JantarMantar. Also  visit Gaitor(  Royal  Cenotaphs ),  Jaigarh  Fort  and  KanakVrindavan  Temple. Visit  Nahargarh  Fort (See  the  sunset view Over the  city). Buffet Diner at hotel and Overnight stay in Jaipur. 

Day 02(17th Dec): JAIPUR – JODHPUR & CAMPING WITH CAMEL RIDE
 Early  morning(around  3  AM)  leave  for  Osian  Village-  the  camping  site(near  Jodhpur). Osian  is known  as “Khajuraho  of  Rajasthan”.   Visit Hindu  and  Jain  Temples such  as Sacchayee  Mata temple,  Sun  temple,  Mahaveera  Jain  temple,  etc.  dating  back  to  8th  to  11th  century. Check-in  the  camp  &  Rest  for  some  time. Late  afternoon snacks and  Camel  Ride  &  gaze  upon  the  sunset in  the  desert. In  the  evening  enjoy  the  cultural  dance  and  bonfire. Diner and overnight stay under the stars in camp. 
 
Day 03(18th  Dec): JODHPUR  EXCURSION & START FOR DELHI
Post  breakfast ,  checkout from  Camp  and  leave  for  full  day  sightseeing  of  Jodhpur. Visit UnmaidBhavan ,Mehrangarh Fort , JaswantThada , Mandore Gardens and Balasamand Lake. Traditional Rajasthani lunch and Evening kept free for shopping and leisure activities. Reach hotel by evening and relax for 3-4 hours. Leave for Delhi by 11 PM after having dinner at Hotel. 
Day 04(19th Dec): TRIP ENDS Arrive at Delhi in the morning.
Cost per head : Rs. 5999/-

11/17/15, 20:19 - Rattandeep Singh: Seating is a verbal noun and a verbal adjective where Sitting is both a verbal noun and a part of verb. Seating describes seating arrangements. 'Is there sufficient seating in this carriage' - (verbal noun). 'The seating arrangements seem to be fine to me' (verbal adjective.) 'We are now taking orders for the first sitting of dinner.' (verbal noun) 'He's sitting on the chair' (part of the verb to sit)

1/23/16, 21:55 - Ritika Bedhara: And the second event of Syaahi’16 is here: the Creative Writing competition.
The online preliminaries are as follows:
Send us a paragraph/poem/prose in 400 characters (NOT WORDS, CHARACTERS) on the topic "Mirror or दर्पण" and send it to us by February 10, midnight.
The selected entries shall face a tougher battle in the offline round on February 13 at DTU campus.
Here is the procedure for participation:
1. Download Fluttr from Google Play Store: http://getfluttr.com/mobile.
2. Post your entries in the channel "Sahitya - DTU Creative Writing Competition" in 'Discover' section.
3. Mention your email ID and contact number. You'll be informed about your selection by 11th February. 
4. For any queries, feel free to mail us at sahitya.dtu@gmail.com
Entries shall be accepted in Hindi and English only.

1/31/16, 11:23 - ‪+91 95602 22255‬: CONSILIUM16
“A picture is a secret about a secret, the more it tells you the less you know.”See, imagine, click.

Play with perspectives, experiment with light, paint pictures with your camera.

Explore concepts of finance and economics, put forward your opinions and ideas through photography. The event is as simple as the name suggests - the participants need to click a photo or two to justify a given theme. 

An event for the out of the box thinker, it challenges the participants’ outlook towards a finance and economics related theme and the now with best possible view of the theme wins the game.

So, put on your thinking caps and participate in one of the most exciting events in Consilium’16.
Please note that evaluation will be on the basis of both the people’s choice (number of likes on the photo) and critics’ choice (perspective behind the photograph and the caption).

It’s the thought behind the picture which matters and not the number of pixels in your camera.

So, put on your thinking caps, participate in CAPTURE and get a chance to win exciting prizes.

Stay tuned for further updates.
https://www.facebook.com/events/1676152899307437/
1/31/16, 12:53 - Paavini: Greetings from Team AYF 2016! 

This mission forms the backdrop of Amity Youth Festival 2016 (AYF’16), which the young students of the University are organizing from February 18th to 20th, 2016. 

The Annual Amity Youth Festival (AYF) links together different knowledge and cultural networks and reinforces the significance of innovation, interaction, information, communication and technology in the society. It helps in uniquely preparing the young Amitians to face the challenges of a competitive world as well as encouraging them to become responsible and engaged citizens. 

AYF is a perfect platform for all young students, invited from all over the country, to display their talent & participate in various competitions both cultural and technical. More than 35 grueling competitions will be conducted during Amity Youth Festival 2016. 

We at Amity believe that AYF’16 would be an experience to remember and an opportunity to form new bonds while celebrating our cherished cultures, heritage and values. 

 
The Fest includes Star Night, Classical Night, International Culture & Food Fest, Inter-Institute Cultural Fest and Competitions, Institutional Events viz., Management and Technical Competitions. 

Cultural Events are as follows:

1. Antaragini (Street Play) - Samarth- 9953458910
2. Aphesia (Battle of Bands) – Harshvardhan- 8802070949
3. Swarmanthan (Solo Singing)- Ajay Malik- 9050002290
4. Broadsway (Stage Play) – Kshitij Sharma- 9873981340
5. Oscillations (Western Dance) - Gunjan- 7503140581
6. Nrityarsh (Classical Dance) –Garima- 8800376631
7. Rang Raise (Folk Dance) – Kasturi- 7042123026
  
Please see our website and the attached list of events and schedule. Please register on-line or through the attached ‘Registration Form’ on or before Friday, 10th February, 2016. 

http://amity.edu/ayf/event.html

3/8/16, 09:29 - Budit Bharadwaj: शब्दों की पोशाक पहनकर
स्याही को संग लेकर
हर कोरा पन्ना अपनेपन से संजो देता है
ये कलम युँ ही चल देता है                                                                   ALFAAZ, the annual poetic bonanza of NSIT is back.
So, all the Ghalibs, Wordsworths and Angelous out there, collect your scribbles, verses, ghazals, satires and sher-o-shayaris, head to NSIT and revive your words with poetry.
This year ALFAAZ would be a two tiered event, with an online round followed by a second recitation round in NSIT on 10th March.
Namaskar to the hindi kavi and welcome to the english poets; both the languages are allowed.
Grab your chance of winning voucher prizes worth Rs. 1500 and much more.
In order spark up the lights a bit more,
this year NSIT Delhi is presenting a Chhatra-Sammelan. Winners of ALFAAZ will get an opportunity to perform in Chhatra-Sammelan (only Hindi entries allowed in Chhatra-Sammelan). The first and the best of its kind.

Hurry up,
last date for registration is 8th march.                                                          Register yourself on the doc below:
https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1ext3pLRu6RHdVMpvAIJCvC2pTRDVdIX9HGGS80iBFDw/edit

3/15/16, 14:35 - Rashmeet: Innerve in collaboration with INFIZEAL Technologies, an IIT Delhi Alumni Venture, (an ISO 9001:2008 certified) is organizing a workshop based on following 2 technologies:-
1. Touch technology
2. Augmented/gesture controlling technology 
  
Following are some important points related to the workshop:-
●Based on Pranav Mistry's six sense device.
●Student of any branch can attend.
●Not related to robotics
●Last year this workshop was held at APIIIT Cudapaahl with a count of 380+ students.
●First time ever in India Touch & Augmented Control Workshop in which student learn
Students will be taught on following aspects:
1) How to convert normal Laptop or Desktop Screen into multi-touch Screen i.e. they will be able to give input through the screen of the laptop/desktop.
2) The image thrown by projector on any surface will be converted into multi-touch surface.
3) To make their own multi-touch pad.
4) To control their laptop with hand gesture movement through the device Microsoft KINECT.
5) Controlling mouse (cursor) with voice.
6) Can Play Virtual Drum
7) To make a Wireless Measuring Tape
8) To capture 3-D Image throw Video
9) To create their own augmented world and play with it

Date: 19th and 20th March
Time: 10:00am to 5:00 pm
Venue: IGDTUW, Kashmere Gate

For details of the workshop:
https://docs.google.com/document/d/1DDPqeLKgbQLmiDEmXMkT7VTuzdS5FInVhrd4e5kfxus/edit?usp=sharing

To register- http://goo.gl/forms/sH8JgJQ7ix

Visit our page- https://www.facebook.com/igdtuwinnerve/

3/19/16, 15:41 - Rohit Jain: Hey         
Triquetra-16,inter college sports fest  jointly organised by DTU, IIIT-D and NSIT to be held from 25th to 27th of March.

Triquetra is a collaborative sports meet, which is a joint initiative by officials and students of IIIT-Delhi, NSIT and DTU. It is an effort by these three leading technical institutes of the NCT of Delhi to jointly organize high quality sporting events in Delhi.

The vision is to provide a competitive platform to college students to showcase their sporting talent. The mission is to capitalize the joint power of the resources of the three institutes to provide a competitive sporting platform to students.

Sports:
Cricket @NSIT
Football @NSIT
Basketball @NSIT
Volleyball @NSIT 
Tennis @IIITD
Table Tennis @IIITD
Badminton @DTU
Athletics @NSIT
Pool @IIITD
Powerlifting @NSIT
Chess @DTU

We eagerly await your confirmation as registration will be on first come first serve basis. 
Anticipating your participation!
Kind Regards,

Amit Kumar Yadav, NSIT (+91-8130900385)
Bavneet Singh, IIIT-Delhi (+91-9899104225)
Vinayak, DTU (+91-9999559153)
On the behalf of the Organizing Committee

4/6/16, 21:27 - ‪+91 85889 04936‬: What is CDF?
CDF is a non-profit organization that aims to bridge the gap between rural and urban India and provide them with a plethora of opportunities. The foundation aims to empower youth and women in rural India through connectivity and entrepreneurship.

Why CDF?
CDF is your chance to hone your innovative skills and make a change in the society. It is your opportunity to contribute and give back to the society along with learning a lot of new things on the way.

Work at CDF:
The work will be implemented in three phases:
Education- educating rural India on health, life skills and technology, business skills etc.
Entrepreneurship/ Employment- creating new employment and business opportunities for women and youth in rural areas.
Connectivity- connecting villages, women groups, youth groups to find mutually beneficial solutions. 

The recruitment will be done in the following departments
Entrepreneurship
Knowledge
Awareness
Initiative
Resources
    
So be there at 4 pm on 7th of April for the orientation of CDF and be a part of it.
Venue: Mini Audi.

4/12/16, 23:20 - Nupur: Graduating from college is a significant rite of passage. For most graduates, it signifies an important transition into the real world of being totally independent and earning a livelihood full-time.
The thought of making it on your own can make you anxious and uncertain about the future.

'Campus to Corporate' by Feather DTU, aims to make the transition easy. It would be a definite boost to your personal contribution and performance levels in the organization. A capable Trainer/ Mentor at this point would bring in the comfort zone for them to familiarize themselves with the work culture. 

'College to Corporate' will be the bridge adding value and providing training on the basics of React Native ( platform to build android and ios apps together )

We are organizing a workshop on 16th and 17th of April.
A professional from IBM will be taking the workshop. It will be an interactive session where you'll learn about react native, how to code for android and ios together, and how to deploy on both the platforms together.
All the attendees will get a participation certificate signed by IBM professional. And we'll have a challenge by the end of the workshop, the winners of which will get prizes worth 10,000 by IBM, a chance to get an INTERNSHIP at IBM and much more. 

The workshop will include a discussion of the differences between React Native and iOS/Android development. And you'll also build a simple mobile application yourself.

To register fill up this form : http://bit.ly/23rLT9Z

Venue: Smart Class L1, L2, DTU Campus.
Timings: 10am- 5pm on 16th and 17th April, total 12 hours workshop.
For enquiries contact: Kartik Gupta (8826655313)

Some are in contact,☎

because of their ego,💁

because of our ego,🙇

N Care 👼🙏😔


  
about them because of the part they played, 👯💏👫 in our life.

no matter how often you talk or how close you are✊👊👌✌

It is the place where a person discovers oneself.

As all the new freshers take residence in their respective hostel rooms.

This hostel room has been abandoned for more than a decade.

This is a true story that has been brought to light by the students of NSIT.

9/4/16, 01:14 - Manu Jindal: A hostel is not just a second home for a student.
It is the place where a person discovers oneself.

As all the new freshers take residence in their respective hostel rooms.
We bring you the story of a hostel room in NSIT, Delhi.
This hostel room has been abandoned for more than a decade.
No one is allotted this room and yet somehow everyone knows the horrors that have occurred here.
This is a true story that has been brought to light by the students of NSIT.

ACM Presents

HOSTEL ROOM D-407

The Finance and Economics Society, in collaboration with Career Launchers, brings to you the CL Young India Challenge - an aptitude test designed to test your smarts in a bid to find the country's best and brightest!

- Four levels of the test with exciting PRIZES at EACH level! 
- Open to all yours - so first or fourth, come along to try your luck ;)
- First level: 29th September, Thursday
- Duration: half an hour
- The exam will be conducted in two slots: 12:30 and 1:30

The test will not only help you gain an understanding of where you stand among your peers, but Career Launchers will be an invaluable asset for guidance on how to craft your way up the professional ladder. 

Moreover, students who qualify for higher levels consisting of Case Interviews, Case Studies etc. will be provided mentorship by FES in the form of dedicated mentors, Mock Case Interview Sessions, and Case Studies. 

So gear up and be ready!

10/13/16, 16:03 - Kaushal: Interested in non-tech but no idea what to do come internships and placements???

Case interviews and guesstimates are the most challenging yet integral part of placement interviews. What is indeed very difficult can be demystified with proper knowledge.The Finance and Economics Society of NSIT is proud to announce a session on Case Interviews and Case Solving.
 
Come and put yourself in the shoes of a consultant, as we teach you to think like one. The session will have a comprehensive approach involving discussions on different frameworks and strategies applied during case interviews.

Practice cases would be the most integral part of the session as cracking case interviews while interacting in groups would be immensely beneficial and a great confidence builder. 
 It will be an all encompassing session which would leave no resource or approach on case interview methods untapped.
 
The session is open for second and third year students and is particularly important for people who will be giving internship or placement interviews.

Venue: 110, Connecting Block at 4:30

Beer Hai Tu.

11/5/16, 18:21 - Manan Pal: External m there were 2 externals in first batch.
Ek bahut difficult Qs puch rha tha.
For my batch (second half) wo wala external lunch krne chala gya and uski jagah ek internal tchr aa gyi thi. To humara second half m kuch logo ka doosre external n liya viva and kuch ka internal ne

From second half:
Explain oc sc test
Voltage regulation of transformer and its change with phase angle of load
Is transformer more efficient or induction motor? (+ 2 reasons)
In blocked rotor test what is value of slip?
Difference between self and separately excited. Why are they called so?
How rotating magnetic field is generated?
Can rotating magnetic field be generated by single phase ac current?
Given a 3 phase supply to stator (say star connection) which produces a rotating magnetic field in say clockwise direction, methods to change it to anticlockwise direction. How will you change it to anticlockwise direction without introduction of any separate circuit element? (ans. By changing configuration. RYB to RBY or vice versa)

From first half
Can slip be negative? (ans. Yes, koi breaking region hota h, search google)
Can slip be >1? (ans. Yes, again google)
Explain principle behind synchronous motor
Principle behind induction motor Single and 3 phase
Principle dc motors
Can induction motor behave as capacitor? (ans. Yes, when in Overexcited state)
Use of squirrel cage mechanism
Explain (naam yaad nhi h) theory (ans. A pulsating magnetic field is equivalent to 2 opposite directional rotating magnetic fields)

Bas itna hi yaad h

11/7/16, 11:42 - Rishab Gupta: Over excitation- In this case, our DC voltage provides more excitation than required so our machine counterbalance that extra flux by setting flux in opposite direction with the help of AC supply and this is called demagnetisation. In this case our machine works on leading power factor and works as a capacitive load.

11/8/16, 20:47 - Rattandeep Singh: LIVE Big announcement by PM Narendra Modi 
- From midnight tonight (Nov 8),  Rs 500 and Rs 1000 notes won't be legal tender anymore.
- For the next 50 days, until 30 Dec 2016,old notes of can be deposited and exchanged at post offices and banks.
- For 72 hours, until Nov 11 midnight, all govt hospitals will accept old Rs 500 and Rs 1000 notes.
- There will be no change in any other form of currency exchange be it cheque, DD, payment via credit or debit cards, online payments, etc.

11/8/16, 21:06 - ‪+91 95602 22255‬: The RBI is unearthing the black money by denying legal tender status. Imagine I am real estate developer stuck with hundreds of crores of rupees in cash (I cannot deposit it in a bank if it exceeds Rs. 50000 without my pan number). This way the RBI prevents these currencies from circulation. The amount of money supply and the velocity of it will be affected. This will have a decelerating effect on prices and may cause deflation.
The RBI knows from its books as to how much of these currencies have been issued. Let us say it is 100 billion rupees. By removing these large bills, and if not replaced, high denominated currencies will become a rare sight.
India has less than 100 banks and a little over 1000000 branches (I don’t have the data). These are 680000 villages. Nearly most of them don’t have a bank. This new policy will be a huge shock for them. All their trades are mostly through currency transaction. The next time they try to take their 500 rupee note dated prior 2005 to trade they will be told that it is not a legal tender and so will not be accepted. Now all these rich land lords and rural politicians have to rush to banks in the city to exchange these higher denominated currencies issued prior to 2005.
Poor understanding of intention of RBI will lead to even shop keepers demanding currencies with a face value of 100 Rs or less for transaction.
Believe it or not, if this policy is implemented most of the illegal and black money used by politicians during election will disappear from circulation once for all.
The policy will not affect 80 to 90 percent of the population. Our per capita GDP is less than 1 lakh rupees. They won’t have much cash in their hands to worry about this new ruling. The bank will always accept a few of these currencies and that will pretty much take care of them.
This is an indirect way of reducing money supply and its velocity. Slowly our country will move towards paperless currency. Every rupee in circulation with then be accounted for and so the local black money can be easily unearthed.
In my personal opinion, this is an important move. It may look innocuous to lots of people but for those who have hoarded wealth in cash, this will be a real headache as to how to convert it.
The linkup between the bank accounts and the income tax department already exists. A rich man with enormous cash, if he approaches the bank to convert, the spot light will be on him.
Many countries have issued new currencies replacing existing ones. Mexico, Argentina, Turkey, Israel, and Germany to name a few have done it in the past. If our government decides to make for example every old 100 Rs note to a new 10 Rs note, then the new 500 or the 1000 rupee denomination will become really scarce.

11/8/16, 21:35 - ‪+91 90139 39226‬: *RBI to issue ₹2000 Rupees Notes coming February 2017*

*Not just a piece of paper There is much more in this note Read the full content of this message*

India is all set to add one more denomination to its currencies shortly. The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) will be issuing Rs 2,000 currency notes, the highest to come into circulation, even as some experts feel7 high-value denominations should be discontinued to curb black money.

The Rs 2000 currency is designed keeping in mind to eradicate the black money issues using state of the art indigenous nano technology, every Rs. 2000 currency note is embedded with a *NGC (Nano GPS Chip)*

*How the embeded NGC Technology Works?*
The unique feature of the NGC is it dosent need any power source. It only acts as a signal reflector. When a Satellite sends a signal requesting location the NGC reflects back the signal from the location, giving precise location coordinates, and the serial number of the currency back to the satellite, this way every NGC embedded currency can be easily tracked & located even if it is kept 120 meters below ground level. The NGC cant be tampered with or removed without damaging the currency note

*How will this help eradicate black money menace?*
Since every NGC embeded currency can be tracked. The satellite can identify the exact amount of money stored at a certain location. If a relatively high concentration of currency is found a certain location for a longer period of time at suspicious locations other than banks & other financial institutions. The information will be passed on to the Income Tax Department for further investigation

*Just a beginning of the end of black money in India*

12/1/16, 20:47 - Paavini: Practical m sheet choose krna tha
Performing was individual
Pehle half of the students performed while the other half wrote on sheet and gave viva
On sheet: Aim, apparatus, theory, circuit diagram, observations (if any), graph (if any), calculations (if any), result, precautions, application of circuit used in expt (eg. Application of clipper, slicer circuits)
Output laana and saare output dikhana zaroori h except possibly for transistor waale; usme agar nhi aaye to circuit dekhke marks lg jate h and then no graph reqd

Viva in groups of 4:
In common collector transistor, bw which terminals is input given and where is output taken?
Values of current and voltage gain for ce and cc configurations
Relationship between alpha, beta and gamma
Difference between bjt and mosfet
Why input resistance of mosfet is high
Which region is transistor operated in for amplifier? Which region for mosfet? Why active for tt and saturation for mosfet?
How is q point maintained in bjt once obtained?

Piv value: Compare for full wave and bridge rectifiers

Given input and output, draw the circuit (which clipper, clamper or rectifier) for which it is obtained 
Draw Vi characteristics of ideal diode

Abhi bas itna hi yaad aa rha h but aur bhi qs the

1/8/17, 21:20 - Buv Misra: D. Swaroop sir has decided to take computer and  preperation courses  for competitive exams this semester.
The schedule for classes will be decided based on the number of students who apply.
Only hardworking and motivated enough should apply. 
The program is open for ECE and COE second year students only.

The three courses that will be covered are:
1)Research and product development
2)Research
3)competitive exams

Product development-
Working on android applications, studying algorithms related to AI, fuzzy logic, number theory, competitons like ICPC etc.(Pre-requisite:JAVA/C++ or any other object oriented language).

Research- 
Sir will be teaching AI, fuzzy logic, ANN, number theory, algebra, theory of commutation etc and will help students come up with research papers. Apart from that Quantum theory, game theory(application), cryptography and machine learning will also be taught, and related zero level research papers.

Competitive exams-
CAT,MAT,UPSC (except GRE,TOEFL)
 
Interested students fill this doc by 11-Jan-2017.
https://goo.gl/forms/gjruriLGZq8JcEtq2

3/23/17, 18:34 - Kaushal: Dear All,
In view of the forthcoming MCD Elections, the semester calendar is modified after discussion with the Director.The following Saturdays / Sundays will be working days for all Faculty, TRF and the Staff members working in the academic departments / divisions / Labs. They have to follow the time table mentioned against the date: 
25/03/2017:                       Monday Time Table
26/03/2017:                       Tuesday Time Table
01/04/2017:                       Wednesday Time Table
08/04/2017:                       Thursday Time Table
09/04/2017:                       Friday Time Table
 
There will be no classes during April 17 – 21, 2017. 
 In compensation, the faculty, TRF and staff mentioned above will avail April 24-28, 2007 as leave.     The practical examinations will be from May 01 to May 05, 2017 and Theory examination will commence from May 08, 2017. Remaining Practical examinations (if any) will resume after Theory Examinations.  The detailed date sheet will be provided at a later stage. 
I request all to cooperate in completing the syllabus in the interest of the Institute. 
 
I also request to all the Heads of the Divisions / Departments to give necessary instructions to the Faculty / Staff / TRF for smooth conduct of the classes. 

With regards

J. Jena


Dr. J. Jena
Professor, Department of Mathematics and
Dean, Academic (UG)
Netaji Subhas Institute of Technology
Sector-3, Dwarka, New Delhi - 110078

4/6/17, 23:20 - PVS Vamsi: Sway in the tunes of LA music

The road less taken, is usually the one involving more risks and struggles. However, it is that path that makes all the difference and sets one apart.

Born into a family of IITians and Physics gold medallists, Lakshay Mohan Gupta (Sitar) & Aayush Mohan Gupta (Sarod), left no stone unturned to pursue their dreams when they found true happiness and purpose in music. Defying stereotypes, they found support in their father, Mr. Shyam Mohan Gupta, Founder Director, VMC.

Lakshay Mohan and Aayush Mohan are grand disciples of Pt. Ravi Shankar.They have also learnt under the tutelage of the legends of Maihar Gharana, such as Padmabhushan Smt. Sharan Rani and Pt. Uma Shankar Mishra and others.

Hailed as one of the most talented musicians by Pt. Jasraj, they have been won many prestigious awards and accolades from all quarters. 

Listen to them share their exciting journey at TEDxNSIT 2017.

#HamareyVMCWaale #16thApril2017

4/18/17, 17:37 - Kaushal: Greetings from The Students' Council, NSIT

We'd like to announce the recruitment for the batch of 2019. The Students' Council fundamentally acts as a communication channel between the college administration and the students. Over the last couple of years the organisation has had a positive impact on many fronts. 

From introducing programs for the benefit of the student community and being their voice in crucial decision making in the administration to spreading awareness on how things go about in the institute and executing events like the Alumni meet and the Open House, the organisation has come a long way since it's inception. 

Over the next few weeks we'll be shortlisting candidates through a rigorous recruitment procedure. The exact details of the same will be released in the next few days on our Facebook page. 
Stay tuned!

4/20/17, 12:15 - Kaushal: Hello all,

Following is the procedure for the first round for those who wish to be a part of the Council:

1. Fill up google doc -->   https://goo.gl/forms/qkkRVJCCZfiOF6T43

2. Send your CV and a Statement of Purpose (SOP) explaining why you wish to join the Students Council.

3. Along with the above mentioned documents, please send in a separate document mentioning the few problems that you feel can be addressed by the Council, along with potential implementation strategy.

4. Also, please send in a scanned copy/photograph of your mark sheets along with a passport size photo.

All these need to be mailed at 'sac.nsit@gmail.com' and "students.council@nsitonline.in" by 2359 hrs, Saturday.

Please note that this recruitment is for 2nd years only.

For any queries, contact: 
Suman Hazra : +91 8588839350, sumanhazra10@gmail.com

Ishaan Dube : +91 8860597845, ishaand.dube@gmail.com
